      <hedline>
        <hl1>Sanctions on Belgrade</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Michael Pravica letter says sanctions against Yugoslavia should be lifted to deprive Slobodan Milosevic of excuses for his failings as a leader (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Milosevic, Trailing in Polls, Rails Against NATO'' (news article, Sept. 20):</p>
        <p>Until the United States adopts a policy toward Yugoslavia that is ''people-friendly'' and ''dictator-unfriendly,'' any efforts made to promote democracy and peace in this vital Balkan country will be viewed with deep suspicion and trepidation by its citizens.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Milosevic, Trailing in Polls, Rails Against NATO'' (news article, Sept. 20):</p>
        <p>Until the United States adopts a policy toward Yugoslavia that is ''people-friendly'' and ''dictator-unfriendly,'' any efforts made to promote democracy and peace in this vital Balkan country will be viewed with deep suspicion and trepidation by its citizens.</p>
        <p>It is time for President Clinton to mend his attitudes toward Yugoslavia and lift the punishing sanctions. Slobodan Milosevic will then be left with no more excuses for his failings as a leader.</p>
        <p>MICHAEL PRAVICA  Las Vegas, N.M., Sept. 20, 2000</p>
      </block>
